  },
  {
    "startTime": 10.0,
    "endTime": 12.0,
    "text": "How on earth do you pronounce this word?"
  },
  {
    "startTime": 14.0,
    "endTime": 20.0,
    "text": "Let's look at the most common pronunciations in American, British and Australian English."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 21.0,
    "endTime": 25.0,
    "text": "In general American English it's water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 26.0,
    "endTime": 27.0,
    "text": "Water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 28.0,
    "endTime": 36.0,
    "text": "The T is a flap T, which means that it's pronounced as a soft D sound."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 37.0,
    "endTime": 37.0,
    "text": "D."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 38.0,
    "endTime": 39.0,
    "text": "Water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 40.0,
    "endTime": 44.0,
    "text": "And yes, the R is pronounced at the end."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 45.0,
    "endTime": 46.0,
    "text": "It's water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 48.0,
    "endTime": 49.0,
    "text": "Water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 50.0,
    "endTime": 52.0,
    "text": "Now let's look at British English."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 52.0,
    "endTime": 57.0,
    "text": "In received pronunciation it's water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 59.0,
    "endTime": 60.0,
    "text": "Water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 61.0,
    "endTime": 70.0,
    "text": "There are also lots of Britons who pronounce the T as a glottal stop, so they say water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 73.0,
    "endTime": 73.0,
    "text": "Water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 74.0,
    "endTime": 81.0,
    "text": "In Australia we either say water, like in received pronunciation."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 83.0,
    "endTime": 83.0,
    "text": "Water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 85.0,
    "endTime": 87.0,
    "text": "Or we use a flap T."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 89.0,
    "endTime": 89.0,
    "text": "Water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 92.0,
    "endTime": 92.0,
    "text": "Water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 94.0,
    "endTime": 105.0,
    "text": "People with stronger Australian accents usually pronounce the T as a glottal stop, so they say water."
  },
  {
    "startTime": 107.0,
    "endTime": 108.0,
    "text": " Water."
  }
]